This paper presents a new data structure, the zipper tree, which is a binary search tree. Therefore, it is most likely to belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The paper also discusses the competitive ratio of the zipper tree, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.AL (Computational Complexity) sub-category. The paper uses information theory to analyze the zipper tree, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category. The paper also discusses worst-case access times, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.CC (Computational Complexity and Cryptography) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the amortized access time, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) sub-category.
